Btw, MSI's motherboard stack confuses me...
Ace: 3 M.2 slots, 4 SATA, 2 USB 2.0, 5 USB 3.2
Creation (E-ATX): 2 M.2 slots, 6 SATA, 2 USB 2.0, 11 USB 3.2
The Ace loses 2 sata slots but gains an M.2, the creation tosses in a shit ton of USB connectors
And then the Godlike, which costs SEVEN HUNDRED DOLLARS, scraps 8 USB connectors on the motherboard
Their stack makes no damn sense
At that point, get the AORUS board
Passively cool chipset (only board that does this), and you get 4 USB 2.0, and 7 USB 3.2

I'd be careful with a Ryzen laptop. First gen Ryzen performance is heavily affected by how fast your RAM is, and laptops tend to skimp out in that area.
there's actually a few ways around the ram speed to get similar performance
So what is the optimal RAM for a Ryzen laptop Robit?
there's a video on Linus Tech Tips recently posted about how to get similar performance to ram that has the higher speeds
which has I think at least two alternative ways to get almost as much performance as you'd get from 3600
Does this involve the channeling of the RAM or is it how the CPU sets it's clock speed based on RAM?
Though looking around, it seems like the 2500U in that laptop is capped at 2400MHz anyways.
Linus was able to get 1600 speed to perform almost as well as 3600
You might be able to find SODIMMs with better latency, but the 2500U is limited to just 2400MHz
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iHJ16hD4ysk it's a good watch. Granted it's all on desktop, but the same alternative things he does with the ram speeds should easily be done on a laptop as well
The advice I always tell people is to make sure you occupy both sides of the RAM channels otherwise you're reducing overall throughput depending on how channeled your m/b is.
since it's about editing things in the bios or editing things via a program in your OS which controls your ram
I just watched that earlier. Definitely one of his more technical videos. I've been around for a while and that video had me rewinding more than a few times to get it all.
I fiigured if anything, a laptop should be able to get at least pretty good performance from the ram in it even if it's not THAT good simply due to alternative measures
Yeah it's all about the FSB ratios. FSB of course got mangled over the years when they relocated the memory controllers.
It became more dependent of the CPU clock.
but things ARE crazy faster these days soooo
I think that was the benefit of "unlocked" CPUs... because you could change the typically hardwired multiplier.
Without messing with the actual CPU speed, which would make for an easily adjustable FSB.
